{{pagebanner|NATO_wikivoyage_banner.png|pgname=North-East Brussels}} The '''North-East''' of [[Brussels]] is a residential and commercial district of [[Belgium]]'s capital, bordering [[Brussels/Schaarbeek|Schaarbeek]] to the south-west and [[Brussels/Woluwe|Woluwe]] to the south. The district is sandwiched between the {{rint|be|rail}} rail yard of Brussels North and the border with [[Flanders]]. It is internationally known for hosting the NATO headquarters of Evere, making the district one of the most powerful military hubs in the world. Aside from the [[#Q579666|Cemetery of Brussels]], this off-the-beaten-track district has a few interesting museums to offer.
==Understand== The district consists of the communes ''Evere'' in its centre, ''Haren'' to the north, and the residential parts of ''Schaarbeek'' to the south-east.
==Get in== ===By train=== The district has 3 train stations: {{marker |type=go |lat=50.8675 |long=4.4007 |name={{station|Evere}} |wikidata=Q2969853 }}, {{marker |type=go |lat=50.8774 |long=4.4097 |name={{station|Bordet}} |wikidata=Q3096028 }}, and {{marker |type=go |lat=50.8889 |long=4.4179 |name={{station|Haren}} |wikidata=Q47317 }}, as well as {{marker |type=go |lat=50.8778 |long=4.3801 |name={{station|Schaarbeek}} |wikidata=Q801418 }} bordering the north-east. The Schaarbeek station is the most frequented station on the line to [[Vilvoorde]], [[Mechelen]], and [[Antwerp]]. All stations are served by Belgian rail operator {{rint|be|rail}} '''NMBS'''/'''SNCB'''.
===By tram=== Tram route {{rint|brussels|62}} stops at [[#Q2969853|Evere station]], and tram {{rint|brussels|92}} stops at [[#Q801418|Schaarbeek station]]. To reach the main tourist attractions (museums), take tram {{rint|brussels|55}} from {{station|Rogier}} direction {{station|Da Vinci}} until {{marker |type=go |lat=50.875935 |long=4.392836 |name={{station|Linde|32|55}} }}, about 30 min. All trams are operated by the {{rint|brussels|MIVB}} '''MIVB'''.
===By bus=== Bus lines {{rint|brussels|45}}, {{rint|brussels|69}}, and {{rint|brussels|80}} traverse the district and have numerous connection points with tram and rail network. Note that many bus lines are operated by the [[Flanders|Flemish]] bus company '''De Lijn''', with an incompatible ticketing system. As a rule of thumb, bus line numbers below 100 are {{rint|brussels|MIVB}} MIVB lines, and line numbers above 100 are De Lijn lines.
===By bicycle=== As in the other districts, bicycle sharing system '''Villo''' has numerous stations where a bike can be dropped off. Cycle time is ca. 30 - 40 min from the Brussels city center, depending on where you want to get in the district.
==Get around== {{mapframe | 50.8728 | 4.4093 | zoom=13}} {{mapshapes|Q506298}}<!--metro--> {{Mapshapes|Q117965|stroke-width=2}} <!-- Brussels S-train --> ===By public transport=== Trams {{rint|brussels|55}} and {{rint|brussels|62}} traverse most of the district, and the fastest mode of point to point transportation. Bus lines {{rint|brussels|64}} and {{rint|brussels|80}} reach the northern parts of the district, but are a slower option. You can take a bus or tram with the same ticket within an hour, since they're both operated by the '''MIVB'''.
===By bicycle=== There are numerous stations for bicycle sharing network '''[http://www.villo.be/Toutes-les-stations/Carte-des-stations Villo]''' in this district, most notably {{marker |type=around |lat=50.87758 |long=4.38041 |name={{station|Elisa}} }} near the Schaarbeek station, {{marker |type=around |lat=50.87089 |long=4.39736 |name={{station|Onze Lieve Vrouw}} }} near the museums at ''Linde'', and {{marker |type=around |lat=50.87697 |long=4.40083 |name={{station|Vrede}} }} near ''Peace Square''.
===On foot=== All the tourist attractions can be reached from any of the train stations on foot within 30 minutes.
==See== * {{see | name=NATO Headquarters | alt= | url=https://www.nato.int/en/about-us/organization/nato-structure/nato-headquarters | email= | address= | lat=50.880000 | long=4.425600 | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | hours= | price= | wikipedia=NATO headquarters | image=NATO-Bruxelles 2014-07-23 21-05.jpg | wikidata=Q12800833 | lastedit=2018-07-20 | content=A large military complex in use as the NATO headquarters. It is off-limits to visitors, and you might get shot on sight when trying to get in, so leave your bombs at the entrance. However, if you're lucky, the gates might be open on the side (closer to the tram stop), where you can get a bit of a better view of the headquarters without a giant metal fence in the way, but don't try to trespass there. }} * {{see | name=Communal Museum of Evere | alt=Gemeentelijk Museum van Evere | url=https://www.uitinvlaanderen.be/agenda/e/gemeentelijk-museum-evere/E836265E-0911-BF70-E3299FC0705138B5 | email= | address=Edward Stuckensstraat 11-13 | lat=50.87585 | long=4.39352 | directions={{station|Linde|32|55}} | phone=+32 2 2454488 | tollfree= | hours=Th 14:00-17:00 | price=Free | wikipedia= | wikidata= | lastedit=2018-07-24 | content=A museum dedicated to the history of the Evere commune, focussing on the political, religious, economical and social life in the area from the Middle Ages to the present. The story of Evere is told through paintings, sculptures, and tools from pre-urbanized times. Many pictures and artifacts guide visitors through the more recent history of Evere and its significance for Brussels. }} [[File:MBMA-Moulin Molen Evere.jpg|thumb|right|The windmill of the ''Museum of Milling and Food'']] * {{see | name=Museum of Milling and Food | alt=Museum van de Molen en de Voeding | url=https://evere.brussels/fr/que-faire/tourisme/moulin-devere | email= | address=Windmolenstraat 21 | lat=50.87325 | long=4.39501 | directions={{station|Linde|32|55}} | phone=+32 2 245 37 79 | tollfree= | hours=W-F 10:00-17:00, Sa-Su 13:00-17:30 | price= | wikipedia=nl:Brussels Museum van de Molen en de Voeding | image=MBMA-Moulin Molen Evere.jpg | wikidata=Q3329505 | lastedit=2018-07-24 | content=Occupying the former windmill of Evere, built in 1841 to grind the grain of surrounding farms. It was hooked up to a steam machine in 1853, making the blades redundant, and they were disassembled shortly afterwards. From 1911 onwards, the mill could no longer compete with larger mills and it lost its function. For the next 20 years, it became a location for various companies and factories unrelated to milling. From 1930 to 1983 most notably, the building served as a spices factory, after which the mill remained empty for 25 years. It gained the status of protected heritage in 1990 and was acquired by the municipality in 1998 which gave it its current function of museum in 2008. It hosts a permanent exhibition of machines and tools used for milling and processing spices, dating from the spices factory era. It also discusses the history of the mill, the development of milling techniques from prehistoric grindstones evolving to millstones and contemporary techniques. The museum also hosts temporary exhibitions that change yearly, ranging from nutritional themes to the history of breakfast, the history of sweets, culinary history of the [[First World War]], forgotten and unusual vegetables, and so on. }} [[File:Cimetière_de_Bruxelles_04.jpg|thumb|right|Portal to the Cemetery of Brussels, honoring fallen Belgian soldiers of the [[First World War]]]] * {{see | name=Cemetery of Brussels | alt= | url= | email= | address= | lat=50.86806 | long=4.41651 | directions={{station|Begraafplaats|63|80|n04}} | phone= | tollfree= | hours= | price= | wikipedia=Brussels_Cemetery | wikidata=Q579666 |image=Cimetière_de_Bruxelles_01.jpg | lastedit=2018-07-23 | content=The cemetery of Brussels is, rather ironically, situated behind the former NATO headquarters complex. Numerous inhabitants of Brussels with a historic significance are buried here, including former mayor [[Brussels/Pentagon#Q14505682|Charles Buls]], and Pierre-Théodore Verhaegen, founder of the Brussels University.}} :* {{see | name=Field of Honour | alt= | url= | email= | address= | lat=50.86840 | long=4.41797 | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | hours= | price= | wikipedia=Second World War | wikidata= | lastedit=2018-07-23 | content=This Field of Honour, located within the cemetery, honours Belgian airmen who died in the [[Second World War]]. It is administered and maintained by the Belgian Ministry of Defence, although the Commonwealth War Graves Commission commemoratively lists 84 of the airmen buried here who died serving in [[Great Britain|British Commonwealth]] air forces following the fall of Belgium to Nazi [[Germany|German]] occupation in 1940. In all over 200 airmen are commemorated here with headstones. Around 30 of those, whose headstones are marked "missing" (in ancient Celtic "disparu"), have no known grave. The cemetery also contains the war graves of 53 British Commonwealth service personnel of the [[First World War]] and 587 from Second World War. Most of the graves from the former war, all within Plot X, are of bodies of prisoners of war exhumed from Germany and reburied here by the [[Canada|Canadian]] Corps in April 1919. Those of the latter war are of troops of the British Expeditionary Force in Belgium in May 1940 before the retreat to [[Dunkirk]], aircrew crashed or shot down over Belgium, and, predominately, those on lines of communication duties after the liberation of Brussels in September 1944. The Commonwealth War Graves Commission are responsible for these graves as well as for 35 Foreign National service burials and 5 non-World War service burials. }} [[File:Cimetière de Bruxelles 02b.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Waterloo]] Campaign Monument at the Cemetery of Brussels]] :* {{see | name=British Waterloo Campaign Monument | alt= | url= | email= | address=Rond Punt der Geallieerden | lat=50.87008 | long=4.41456 | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | hours= | price= | wikipedia= | wikidata=Q20949761 | lastedit=2018-07-23 | content=Monument for [[Great Britain|British]] officers killed during the [[Waterloo]] Campaign of 1815. After being suggested in 1861,the City Council of Brussels approved to donate about 30 m² of cemetery to re-bury British officers whose graves were in or around Brussels, and on cemeteries around the battlefields of Waterloo and Quatre Bras. Queen Victoria personally oversaw the funding of a suitable monument. The sculpture, a design of Belgian artist Jacques de Lalaing, is a large edifice of bronze figures on a plinth of stone blocks. It depicts Britannia with her helmet and trident lowered, surrounded by weapons, uniforms and equipment. Inscribed to the sides of the plinth are shields bearing the names of the regiments that participated in the campaign. The monument was unveiled in 1890, with below it a crypt with 16 niches. It now contain 17 bodies, all of which were transferred here between 1890 and 1894. Of the 17 men, all but one died during the campaign: Sergeant-Major Edward Cotton survived the battle and became a tourist guide to the battlefields after the campaign. He was buried at Hougomont after his death in 1849 and also transferred to the Monument. }} [[File:Cimetière de Bruxelles 10.jpg|thumb|right|Innovation disaster memorial at the Cemetery of Brussels]] :* {{see | name=Memorial for the Victims of the Innovation Disaster | alt= | url= | email= | address=Rond Punt der Burgemeesters | lat=50.86699 | long=4.41758 | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price= | wikipedia=L'Innovation Department Store fire | image=Cimetière de Bruxelles 10.jpg | wikidata=Q2794675 | lastedit=2018-07-24 | content=Memorial dedicated to the 251 victims who perished in the flames of the [[Brussels/Pentagon#Q2794675|Innovation]] disaster of 22 May 1967. It was erected in 1968 and consists of 4 white marble columns with the names of the victims engraved. }} * {{see | name=Train World | alt= | url=http://trainworld.be | email= | address=Prinses Elisabethplein 5, Schaarbeek | lat=50.87886 | long=4.38106 | directions=In and next to the Schaarbeek train station. Take the train or the tram {{rint|brussels|92}} until its terminus station {{station|Schaarbeek station}} | phone= | tollfree= | hours=Tu-Su 10:00 - 17:00 | price=€12 | wikipedia=Train World | image=Stoomlocomotieven.jpg | wikidata=Q14931504 | lastedit=2019-02-12 | content=Belgian train museum, opened in September 2015. Interesting collection of Belgian railway exhibits, including an entire former railwayman's house which once stood on the site and had the museum constructed around it. Notable for its dramatic interior decor by local artist François Schuiten }}
