==Go next== Other districts of [[Brussels]] adjacent to the North-East district include: * {{marker |type=vicinity |lat=50.8594 |long=4.3770 |name=[[Brussels/Schaarbeek|Schaarbeek]]|wikidata=Q12887}}, a residential area to the south-west, with impressive architecture, and the Brussels Red Lights District. * {{marker |type=vicinity |lat=50.8473 |long=4.4285 |name=[[Brussels/Woluwe|Woluwe]]|wikidata=Q60657887}}, laid back residential area with neat tree lined boulevards, {{UNESCO}} class architectural sights, and excellent restaurants. Several adjacent towns in [[Flanders]] are also worth a day trip: * {{marker |type=city |lat=50.9358 |long=4.3645 |name=[[Grimbergen]]|wikidata=Q633063}} to the north-west, with an impressive abbey, public lunar observatory, and world class spa. * {{marker |type=city |lat=50.8613 |long=4.4673 |name=[[Kraainem]]|wikidata=Q839023}} to the east, easily reachable by Villo or bus, one of the earliest sites of industrialization around Brussels. * {{marker |type=city |lat=50.9308 |long=4.4299 |name=[[Vilvoorde]]|wikidata=Q318418}} to the north, a former manufacturing hub of the car industry, nowadays overrun by immigrants. * {{marker |type=city |lat=50.8242 |long=4.5135 |name=[[Tervuren]]|wikidata=Q456544}} to the south, an authentic town on the outskirts of the [[Brussels/Sonian Forest|Sonian Forest]].
